title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Lemma 3.1.1</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> be a positive integer, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{0},…,a_{n}\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> be complex numbers with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{n}\neq 0]]></fr:tex>. Then the polynomial equation
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[a_{n}z^{n}+…+a_{1}z+a_{0}=0]]></fr:tex>
has at least one solution in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>(It seems like every field has its own proof of the fundamental theorem of algebra, so I will link them here:)</fr:p><fr:ul><fr:li>Proof: <fr:link
